Chet,<br><br>
Part of the process is blowing off some steam. What better place to do it than with people who understand! You need make no apologies. It really relieves tension and puts us back on track again.<br><br>
I have been laid up with the flu for a while, and am now getting back up on my feet. I have been watching the dialogs, nonetheless. If I had felt better I would have flung a few Northern cow chips myself.<br><br>
Cook:<br><br>
You sound just like my grandfather! &lt;a compliment&gt; <br><br>
My grandfather was a sailor from 1919 to 1922 and a Marine from 1922 to 1925, and his diary has references to Vladivostok, Bolsheviks, Manila, Canton, fighting the Chinese in Hunan Province, etc.<br><br>
Just befor I left for 'Nam, we had a man to man talk about the &quot;Far East&quot;. He was worried. He did not in any way feel that what I was about to do was wrong, he was very proud of it in fact, he just had a feeling that something was &quot;not quite right&quot; with the conflict. I left for 'Nam with his personal advice and his personal herbal remedy for we all know what!<br><br>
Since his death, in his private papers I found a poem &quot;The Far East&quot; written &quot;by a Marine&quot;. It was typed on some ancient typewriter and the paper is yellow and has the smell of age. The poem, which I date from the 1920's, is strangely prophetic, and kind of gives me the creeps. It is from a different time and a very different world. What follows is an exact copy, mistakes included: <br><br>
-------------<br><br>
The Far East<br>
By A Marine<br><br>
By the mud hole down in Suvic<br>
Looking lazily at the bay,<br>
There's a goo goo dame awaiting,<br>
And I think I hear her say:<br>
Come you back you malo soldier,<br>
Come you back from o'er the sea.<br>
Come you back and pay your jawbone,<br>
Porague you jawbone me.<br><br>
Her dirty skirt is baggy,<br>
Just reaching to her knees.<br>
Her hair is black and greasy<br>
And is full of bugs and fleas.<br>
Her teeth are red with beetle-nut,<br>
As colored as with dark red paint,<br>
Her name is Noseless Annie<br>
Just like her parent Saint.<br><br>
When the rain fills up the rice fields,<br>
and soaks us to the skin,<br>
Then we all go down to Annies<br>
And tank up on square-face gin.<br>
With her arms around my shoulders,<br>
And her cheeks to mine pressed close,<br>
And I smell her breath &quot;Oh Glory&quot;<br>
How I love to hold my nose.<br>
But I'll leave this all behind me,<br>
Thank God I'll soon be far away,<br>
Back there in God's own country.<br>
And you bet your boots I'll stay.<br>
And I've learnt in my old home town;<br>
That the folks are wise who say,<br>
When you hear the Far East calling,<br>
Just be wise and stay away.<br><br>
------------<br><br>
When I returned from 'Nam, my grandfather chased me for a while for a photograph of me in uniform. I never wanted one taken. After the fall of Saigon, he told me that he understood my feelings, but he never once let me get away without telling me how proud of me he was.<br><br>
Cook, I know you can be counted on to keep up your point of view! <br><br>
Edward:<br><br>
Thanks for your very thoughtful reminder of reality. I go back into my trauma processing group tomorrow, and that is a reality for which I am scared. I think fear is a component of the reason why some of your concerns have not surfaced as individual threads. Also, it is my personal experience on this site since it began that the diverse mix of the participants has kept the subjects to larger issues of philosophy and politics. From time to time, however, most of us have gotten down to the nitty-gritty. My psychologist once remarked on how large was the issue, on an exterior level, and on the interior level of my mind.<br><br>
Edward, pick a topic, create a thread, communicate your feelings, and see where it runs. With many of the subjects you mentioned in your post I have intimate familiarity, and would support your effort.<br><br>
See what happens when the flu goes and oxygen gets back into the brain!<br><br>
Art<br><br>
